principle_desc_en:
Arithmetic sequence: \(a_n = a_1 + (n-1)d\) (for example, when \(a_1=5, d=3\), the sequence is \(5,8,11,\dots\));  
Geometric sequence: \(a_n = a_1 \cdot r^{n-1}\) (for example, when \(a_1=2, r=3\), the sequence is \(2,6,18,\dots\));  
Square number sequence: \(a_n = n^2\) (generates \(1,4,9,16,\dots\));  
Harmonic sequence: \(a_n = \frac{1}{n}\) (generates \(1,\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{3},\dots\)).

Increasing sequence: \(a_{n+1} > a_n\) (e.g., \(a_n=2n\), \(2,4,6,\dots\));  
Decreasing sequence: \(a_{n+1} < a_n\) (e.g., \(a_n=\frac{1}{n}\), \(1,\frac{1}{2},\frac{1}{3},\dots\));  
Constant sequence: \(a_{n+1} = a_n\) (e.g., \(a_n=5\), always 5)

First quadrant: All trigonometric function values are positive (all positive);  
Second quadrant: Only sine is positive (sine);  
Third quadrant: Only tangent is positive (tangent);  
Fourth quadrant: Only cosine is positive (cosine)

① All three sides are equal (e.g., AB = BC = CA);  
② All three angles are equal to 60° (e.g., ∠A = ∠B = ∠C = 60°);  
③ An isosceles triangle with one angle equal to 60° (e.g., if isosceles △ABC has ∠A = 60°, then it must be equilateral).

k>0: The line inclines upward to the right;  
k<0: The line inclines downward to the right;  
k=0: Horizontal line;  
The greater the absolute value of the slope k, the steeper the line.

Standard equation of an ellipse: foci on the x-axis \[\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1 \quad (a > b > 0)\], foci on the y-axis \[\frac{y^2}{a^2} + \frac{x^2}{b^2} = 1 \quad (a > b > 0)\];  
Standard equation of a hyperbola: foci on the \(x\)-axis \[\frac{x^2}{a^2} - \frac{y^2}{b^2}= 1\], foci on the y-axis \[\frac{y^2}{a^2} - \frac{x^2}{b^2} = 1\];  
Standard equation of a parabola: opening to the left or right \(y^2 = \pm 2px \quad (p > 0)\), opening upward or downward \(x^2 = \pm 2py \quad (p > 0)\).

Point on the parabola: The point \((x_0, y_0)\) satisfies the equation \(y_0^2 = 4a x_0\) or \(x_0^2 = 4a y_0\) (Example: the point \((1, 2)\) is on the parabola \(y^2 = 8x\) because \(2^2 = 8 \times 1\));  
Point inside: Substitute into the equation to get \(y_0^2 < 4a x_0\) (when the parabola opens to the right) or \(x_0^2 < 4a y_0\) (when the parabola opens upward) (Example: the point \((1, 1)\) is inside \(y^2 = 8x\) because \(1 < 8\));  
Point outside: Substitute into the equation to get \(y_0^2 > 4a x_0\) or \(x_0^2 > 4a y_0\) (Example: the point \((3, 5)\) is outside \(y^2 = 8x\) because \(25 > 24\)).
